**CP: Problem Statement and Dataset**

**Introduction**

Life expectancy is a fundamental indicator of a nation’s overall health and development, reflecting the cumulative impact of social, economic, environmental, and healthcare factors. Over the past century, global life expectancy has increased significantly due to advancements in medical care, sanitation, nutrition, and public health policies. However, these gains are not uniform, with disparities persisting both between and within countries. Understanding the determinants of life expectancy is therefore crucial for policymakers aiming to enhance public health outcomes and address health inequities (Rahman, Rana, & Khanam, 2022; Liu & Zhong, 2024).

Recent studies have highlighted a wide range of factors influencing life expectancy. Economic indicators such as Gross Domestic Product (GDP) per capita positively correlate with life expectancy, suggesting that wealthier nations can invest more in healthcare and social services. Conversely, environmental factors, including air pollution and limited access to clean water, negatively affect life expectancy (Rahman et al., 2022). Lifestyle choices such as smoking and obesity also significantly impact mortality rates, further shaping national life expectancy trends (Time, 2018; Time, 2014). Additionally, social determinants, including education, income inequality, and healthcare access, underscore the complex interplay of factors that influence population health (Gutin, 2021).

The application of predictive modeling techniques has become increasingly prevalent in forecasting life expectancy trends. These models use historical data to estimate future outcomes, providing valuable insights for public health planning and resource allocation (Osei-Kusi, Wu, Tetteh, & Castillo, 2024). Building on this, the current study aims to develop predictive models that estimate national life expectancy at birth, incorporating key socio-economic, health, and governance indicators identified in the literature. The study will assess the model’s performance across countries and time periods to ensure accuracy and robustness. Beyond prediction, it will identify the most influential factors shaping life expectancy, offering evidence-based insights to guide governments, health organizations, and international development agencies in designing policies that promote sustainable improvements in population health (Avendano & Kawachi, 2014; Bosworth, 2018; Harper, 2021).

**Problem**

The primary goal of this project is to predict national life expectancy and identify the socio-economic, health, and governance factors that most strongly influence it. Life expectancy is widely recognized as a key indicator of a nation’s overall development and well-being, yet it is shaped by a complex interplay of variables that extend beyond healthcare alone (Rahman, Rana, & Khanam, 2022; Liu & Zhong, 2024). Factors such as income, education, health expenditure, social support, and perceptions of corruption have been shown to affect life expectancy, but their relative contributions remain underexplored across countries and time periods (Avendano & Kawachi, 2014; Bosworth, 2018; Harper, 2021).

This project seeks to provide a systematic analysis of these determinants, offering predictive insights that can inform evidence-based decision-making. Governments, non-governmental organizations (NGOs), and international development agencies can leverage these findings to design targeted policies, prioritize interventions, and allocate resources more effectively. By identifying the most influential drivers of life expectancy, the study aims to support strategies that improve population health, reduce inequalities between nations, and promote sustainable development outcomes (Time, 2018; Osei-Kusi, Wu, Tetteh, & Castillo, 2024).

**Dataset Description**

**World Bank – World Development Indicators**

The data for this study is drawn from three reputable sources. The first is the World Bank’s World Development Indicators (WDI), which includes important indicators like GDP per capita (Current US$), current health expenditure (% of GDP), current health expenditure (% of GDP), current health expenditure per capita (current US$), current education expenditure, total (% of total expenditure in public institutions), and life expectancy at birth, total (years). This dataset covers more than 200 countries, with annual records dating as far back as the 1960s, and contains hundreds of socio-economic indicators. The following screenshot demonstrates selecting only 63 countries with their indicators from 1960 to present.

**Kaggle – World Happiness Report**  
The second source is the World Happiness Report, available through Kaggle, which adds a social perspective to the analysis. It includes measures such as social support, generosity, and perceptions of corruption, covering approximately 150 countries annually since 2015\. These variables provide insight into how social conditions and governance may influence life expectancy beyond purely economic or health indicators. It contains around 6-10 core variables per year, depending on the dataset version. It records about 150+ countries per year, usually from 2015 onward.

![][image2]

**UNDP – Human Development Index (HDI)**

Finally, the UNDP Human Development Index (HDI) dataset contributes education-related measures, most notably mean years of schooling (MYS) and expected years of schooling (EYS). These indicators are published annually for around 190 countries, dating back to 1990, and provide a critical dimension for understanding the role of education in shaping long-term health outcomes.  
![][image3]

**Justification**

The selected datasets collectively provide a robust and complementary set of predictors for analyzing national life expectancy. World Bank indicators capture the economic and health-financing dimensions, offering key insights into how a country’s wealth and health expenditure influence population health. The UNDP Human Development Index (HDI) provides high-quality education indicators, reflecting the impact of educational attainment on life expectancy. Meanwhile, the World Happiness Report introduces social and governance-related measures, including social support, trust, and perceptions of corruption, which have been shown to affect population well-being.

By integrating these datasets by country and year, the resulting dataset ensures comprehensive coverage of economic, social, health, and educational dimensions, enabling a holistic analysis of life expectancy determinants. This integration provides sufficient features to train both interpretable models, such as multiple linear regression, and more advanced machine learning models, such as gradient boosting.

This approach not only enhances predictive accuracy but also allows for a clear understanding of the relative importance of different predictors. Consequently, the findings will be both practical and actionable, offering evidence-based guidance for policymakers, governments, non-governmental organizations, and international development agencies to design targeted interventions and improve population health outcomes.
